=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer=
=2Eio&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) th=
e New York Post, especially at JPMorg=
an Chase, where Jamie Dimon is slated to receive a $50 million picker-upper=
 if he stays at the bank until 2026; and at Goldman Sachs, where David
Solomon just received an $80 million stock grant that vests in 2030. (That=
=E2=80=99s on top of the $39 million in total compensation each C.E.O. rece=
ived in 2024.)

An equities trader at Goldman told the Post, =E2=80=9CWhen news of Solomon=
=E2=80=99s bonus was released, a lot of folks here just rolled their eyes. =
Of course, that is where our money went.=E2=80=9D The trader also complaine=
d that Goldman was like a =E2=80=9Ccult=E2=80=9D that keeps employees aroun=
d by =E2=80=9Cpromising us promotions or money.=E2=80=9D On bonus
day, the paper reports, some Goldman employees =E2=80=9Cclocked out early=
=E2=80=9D as a form of protest. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a lot of frustrati=
on, anger, and disappointment,=E2=80=9D said one banker. =E2=80=9CIt feels =
demotivating when leadership seems more focused on external perceptions tha=
n internal morale.=E2=80=9D

Over on Wall Street Oasis, the industry message board, a first-year associa=
te whined about getting a $135,000 bonus on top of his $200,000 base salary=
, posting that he or she (but probably he) was =E2=80=9Cnot happy with the
number,=E2=80=9D and that he=E2=80=99d been =E2=80=9Cexpecting more given t=
he strong earnings.=E2=80=9D Another banker =E2=80=9Cseethed=E2=80=9D accor=
ding to the Post, saying, =E2=80=9CThe bottom line for 2024 comp is this: t=
he firm crushed it and a lot of people who made it happen were given cheap =
seats at the celebration.=E2=80=9D

The crocodile tears are killing me. First of all, as everyone surely knows =
by now, Wall Street bankers and traders get paid plenty, and have for decad=
es, especially given that most of these firms are no
longer private partnerships and none of these people have their own capital=
 on the line. Where else can you get paid millions in annual compensation a=
nd not take any risk with your own money? The answer, of course, is nowhere=
=2E But there is always complaining, la=
rgely because Wall Street is the ultim=
ate zero-sum environment, where everyone measures themselves on a relative =
basis, trying desperately to figure out how they stack up to their floor-ma=
tes, never giving a thought to how their
pay compares to that of people in the real world. And since the yearly bonu=
s pool is always a fixed amount, if someone else gets more, you get less.=
=C2=A0

During my years at Lazard, when it was still a private partnership, the exp=
ression was, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not enough for you to succeed; others ha=
ve to fail.=E2=80=9D To drive that point home, every year Michel David-Weil=
l, whose family had owned the firm through four generations, published the =
percentage of the pretax profits that the
Lazard partners got paid each year. If you don=E2=80=99t think that list ma=
de grown men (and a very few women) go nuts, I=E2=80=99ve got news for you.=
 Still, they were all getting paid more than they could ever dream of makin=
g by doing something else.

So I say: Chill out, friends. Revel in your bank accounts, and hunker down =
for the year ahead. We all know you ain=E2=80=99t going anywhere.

