Yes, yes, DeepSeek=E2=80=99s low-cost alternative to ChatGPT might represen=
t a sea change in how
Wall Street models the financial impact of artificial intelligence. Markets=
 like moats, after all. But investors racing for the exits ought to take th=
e long view of history and stop losing their heads.=C2=A0

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

As the Nasdaq sank on Monday over fears that DeepSeek, a Chinese company, m=
ight undercut
the entire American A.I. industry with its free, open-source alternative to=
 ChatGPT, my old J.P. Morgan partner Tom Lee, now the head of research at F=
undstrat Global Advisors, went on CNBC to offer some words of advice. Yes, =
he acknowledged, Nvidia had lost some $600 billion of market value=E2=80=94=
the largest single-day drop for any company ever=E2=80=94and every A.I.-adj=
acent tech stock from Meta to Microsoft was being dumped by investors. =E2=
=80=9CMarkets don=E2=80=99t like uncertainty,=E2=80=9D
Tom observed, calmly. =E2=80=9CThey like moats.=E2=80=9D Nevertheless, =E2=
=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s an overreaction,=E2=80=9D he argued. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99=
d be looking at this as an opportunity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, Tom was right. Yesterday the markets recovered some of what was =
lost on Monday, as people started returning to their senses. Personally, I =
love a market overreaction, especially when it comes after a prolonged, and=
 largely inexplicable, period of
irrational exuberance, in the argot of former Fed chairman Alan Greenspan. =
And that=E2=80=99s certainly what we=E2=80=99ve experienced for the past fi=
ve years in the equities market=E2=80=94an extraordinary 86 percent run top=
ped off by bona fide investor euphoria over the prospect that artificial in=
telligence will supercharge U.S. productivity and usher in some techno-utop=
ia. The Nasdaq is up more than 136 percent in that time.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

This isn=E2=80=99t investment advice, but it=E2=80=99s worth taking the lon=
g view of history. In my own career, I=E2=80=99ve lived through the 1987 cr=
ash; the 1989-93 credit crunch; the freak-out of 1998; the implosion of Lon=
g-Term Capital Management; the dot com bubble; September 11; the 2008 finan=
cial crisis; and most recently, the Covid pandemic, when stocks crashed and=
 interest rates spiked before the Federal Reserve took control yet again,
flooding the zone with liquidity and cheap money.

Every time, the correct move (market-wise, anyway) was not to panic, but to=
 keep calm and carry on. I often return to Warren Buffett=E2=80=99s sage ad=
vice, =E2=80=9Cto be fearful when others are greedy and to be greedy only w=
hen others are fearful.=E2=80=9D I think that=E2=80=99s the correct disposi=
tion in this moment, too.

The
Untouchables
------------

That=E2=80=99s not to say that Silicon Valley has nothing to fear from comp=
etition in
China, or that Wall Street shouldn=E2=80=99t be reassessing its models for =
how much value will accrue from A.I. to the Magnificent Seven: Apple, Micro=
soft, Alphabet, Amazon, Meta, Nvidia, and Tesla, which collectively shed ab=
out $1 trillion of equity value on Monday. For the past year, investors hav=
e rapidly bid up the market capitalization of companies with a stake in the=
 A.I. gold rush, presuming that the massive capex required to build data ce=
nters and train new L.L.M.s would benefit the incumbent
oligopoly. Indeed, the $500 billion =E2=80=9CStargate=E2=80=9D joint ventur=
e that Donald Trump announced last week with OpenAI, Oracle, and SoftBank=
=E2=80=94to build data centers and expand electricity generation capacity=
=E2=80=94is premised on the notion that winning the A.I. war will require i=
nvestment on par with the Manhattan Project.

=C2=A0

Then, last week, word spread that DeepSeek=E2=80=94a side project funded by=
 a
Chinese hedge fund=E2=80=94had created a model comparable to OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s GPT-4o for a fraction of the cost and requiring a tenth of the computi=
ng power that Nvidia specializes in providing. DeepSeek=E2=80=99s chatbot q=
uickly shot to No. 1 in Apple=E2=80=99s app store. Investors in a variety o=
f technology stocks freaked out and ran for the exits. The world=E2=80=99s =
500 richest people supposedly lost $108 billion of wealth on Monday, led by=
 Larry Ellison, whose net worth declined by $22.6 billion; and
Jensen Huang, Nvidia=E2=80=99s co-founder, who lost $20 billion, or some 20=
 percent of his fortune. Elon Musk lost $6.4 billion of his net worth on Mo=
nday. Of course, they all remain impossibly wealthy=E2=80=94so wealthy, in =
fact, that these one-day losses are basically immaterial to them. The Nasda=
q is down again today, but it=E2=80=99s still more or less flat over the pa=
st two months.=C2=A0

Still, it=E2=80=99s no surprise that DeepSeek=E2=80=99s breakthrough, which=
 some
V.C.s are likening to a =E2=80=9CSputnik moment=E2=80=9D for the U.S. tech =
sector, is reverberating in the market, forcing executives and investors to=
 modulate their A.I. euphoria and reassess their assumptions. While Microso=
ft and OpenAI are investigating whether the Chinese insurgent piggybacked o=
n their models to build its own (that=E2=80=99s rich=E2=80=A6), the real sh=
ock is the implication that the cost of A.I. may not scale along with deman=
d. =E2=80=9CJevons paradox strikes again!=E2=80=9D Satya Nadella, the
C.E.O. of Microsoft, wrote Monday on LinkedIn, referring to the theory that=
 =E2=80=9Cas A.I. gets more efficient and accessible,=E2=80=9D it will be r=
educed to a commodity. Great news for markets in the long term, although pe=
rhaps a short-term problem for Nvidia.

Fire,
Ready, Aim
----------

One faithful Wall Street eminence, a lusty contrarian, wrote to me on Monda=
y that his
=E2=80=9Cdecades=E2=80=9D of market experience has led him to the conclusio=
n that =E2=80=9Cstocks have their sharpest drops from their highest peaks w=
hen all see only upside.=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99d say we experienced a healthy =
dose of reality on Monday. I think we have a few more doses to take before =
we=E2=80=99re done here, even if in the longer run, owning stocks=E2=80=94a=
t least over the past 45 years or so=E2=80=94has proved to be a major wealt=
h generator.

=C2=A0

As the
dust settles after Monday=E2=80=99s selloff, I=E2=80=99ve noticed some cool=
er, perhaps wiser, heads prevailing. BNP Paribas Securities=E2=80=99 chief =
U.S. economist, James Egelhof, wrote that the DeepSeek breakthrough will be=
 good news in the long run. =E2=80=9CWe think cheaper A.I. means more A.I.,=
 more quickly,=E2=80=9D he wrote. =E2=80=9CThis should mean a greater and m=
ore rapid productivity boom as the A.I. rollout snowballs. We are not conce=
rned about recession risks directly ensuing from, for example, reduced inve=
stment
in data centers, and we think software investment might rise to offset decl=
ines in data center investment.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Then there=E2=80=99s Pat Gelsinger, the former C.E.O. of Intel, who knows a=
 thing or two about chips and falling off a high perch. (Intel, which has h=
ad its lunch almost completely eaten by Nvidia, is often mentioned as a tak=
eover candidate these days.) =E2=80=9CWisdom is learning the lessons we
thought we already knew,=E2=80=9D he posted ( https://x.com/PGelsinger/stat=
us/1883896837427585035?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F=
25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F29%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on=
 X on Monday, saying DeepSeek offers three lessons. First, computing =E2=80=
=9Cobeys the gas law=E2=80=94[m]aking it dramatically cheaper will expand t=
he market for it. The markets are getting it wrong, this will make A.I. muc=
h more broadly deployed.=E2=80=9D Second, =E2=80=9C[e]ngineering is about c=
onstraints. The Chinese engineers had limited resources and had to find
creative solutions.=E2=80=9D And, finally, =E2=80=9COpen Wins.=E2=80=9D Dee=
pSeek, Gelsinger said, will help =E2=80=9Creset the increasingly closed wor=
ld of foundational A.I. model work.=E2=80=9D He signed off, =E2=80=9CThank =
you DeepSeek team.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0

Tom Lee, despite being a perennial bull, has been pretty much right to be e=
xuberant for the 34 years or so he=E2=80=99s been studying and commenting o=
n the stock market. I think we=E2=80=99re still in need of a major correcti=
on, myself=E2=80=94especially in a number of these crazy meme
stocks, such as Tesla and MicroStrategy, among many others, which have gott=
en far out over their skis for no good reason. But Lee said something else =
on CNBC that stuck with me. =E2=80=9CMarkets just generally do fire, ready,=
 aim,=E2=80=9D he remarked, quoting the old Wall Street truism. That=E2=80=
=99s what happened on Monday.

