ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">That=E2=80=99s not to say that Silicon Valley has <em>nothing</em> to f=
ear from competition in
China, or that Wall Street shouldn=E2=80=99t be reassessing its models for =
how much value will accrue from A.I. to the Magnificent Seven: Apple, Micro=
soft, Alphabet, Amazon, Meta, Nvidia, and Tesla, which collectively shed ab=
out $1 trillion of equity value on Monday. For the past year, investors hav=
e rapidly bid up the market capitalization of companies with a stake in the=
 A.I. gold rush, presuming that the massive capex required to build data ce=
nters and train new L.L.M.s would benefit the incumbent
oligopoly. Indeed, the $500 billion =E2=80=9CStargate=E2=80=9D joint ventur=
e that <strong>Donald Trump</strong> announced last week with OpenAI, Oracl=
e, and SoftBank=E2=80=94to build data centers and expand electricity genera=
tion capacity=E2=80=94is premised on the notion that winning the A.I. war w=
ill require investment on par with the Manhattan Project.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">Then, last week, word spread that DeepSeek=E2=80=94a <em>side project</e=
m> funded by a
Chinese hedge fund=E2=80=94had created a model comparable to OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s GPT-4o for a fraction of the cost and requiring a <em>tenth </em>of th=
e computing power that Nvidia specializes in providing. DeepSeek=E2=80=99s =
chatbot quickly shot to No. 1 in Apple=E2=80=99s app store. Investors in a =
variety of technology stocks freaked out and ran for the exits. The world=
=E2=80=99s 500 richest people supposedly lost $108 billion of wealth on Mon=
day, led by <strong>Larry Ellison</strong>, whose net worth declined by $22=
=2E6 billion; and
<strong>Jensen Huang</strong>, Nvidia=E2=80=99s co-founder, who lost $20 bi=
llion, or some 20 percent of his fortune. <strong>Elon Musk</strong> lost $=
6.4 billion of his net worth on Monday. Of course, they all remain impossib=
ly wealthy=E2=80=94so wealthy, in fact, that these one-day losses are basic=
ally immaterial to them. The Nasdaq is down again today, but it=E2=80=99s s=
till more or less flat over the past two months.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;"><br/>Still, it=E2=80=99s no surprise that DeepSeek=E2=80=99s breakthr=
ough, which some
V.C.s are likening to a =E2=80=9CSputnik moment=E2=80=9D for the U.S. tech =
sector, is reverberating in the market, forcing executives and investors to=
 modulate their A.I. euphoria and reassess their assumptions. While Microso=
ft and OpenAI are investigating whether the Chinese insurgent piggybacked o=
n their models to build its own (that=E2=80=99s rich=E2=80=A6), the real sh=
ock is the implication that the <em>cost</em> of A.I. may not scale along w=
ith demand. =E2=80=9CJevons paradox strikes again!=E2=80=9D <strong>Satya N=
adella</strong>, the
C.E.O. of Microsoft, wrote Monday on LinkedIn, referring to the theory that=
 =E2=80=9Cas A.I. gets more efficient and accessible,=E2=80=9D it will be r=
educed to a commodity. Great news for markets in the long term, although pe=
rhaps a short-term problem for Nvidia.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
